                  <h2>Saving </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>Let him who would enjoy a good future waste none of his present. –Roger Babson</small></p>
                  <p>
                    The money you save for retirement will be either <strong>pre-tax</strong> or <strong>after tax</strong> money.  
                  </p>
                    <dl class="dl-horizontal">
                      <dt><a href="http://wiki.fool.com/Pre-tax" target="_blank">Pre-tax money</a></dt>
                      <dd>is money set aside for retirement before paying Federal and State taxes.  Pre-tax money is typically not paid to you, but instead directly deposited into a retirement account.
                        A <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/401(k)" target="_blank">401(k)</a> or
                        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traditional_IRA" target="_blank">Traditional IRA</a> are common accounts for pre-tax retirement savings.
                        Money withdrawn from a pre-tax account during retirement will be taxed as income, and will grow with
                        <a href="http://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/taxdeferred.asp" target="_blank">taxes deferred</a> until retirement which can be a huge benefit.
                      </dd>
                      <dt>After tax money</dt>
                      <dd>is money in your paycheck after Federal and State taxes have been taken out.  One common after tax retirement savings option is the 
                        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roth_IRA" target="_blank">Roth IRA</a> which can allow your savings to grow 
                        <a href="http://www.fool.com/money/allaboutiras/allaboutiras06.htm" target="_blank">tax free</a>.
                      </dd>
                    </dl>
                  <p>
                    The money you are saving will be subtracted from your income so that your budget reflects your actual living expenses.  
                    This allows you to more accurately compare your living expenses now to your future budget.  After all, you won't need to save for retirement in retirement so this lets you compare how much
                    you're spending now with how much you can spend in retirement.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Add up your <strong>pre-tax</strong> and <strong>after tax</strong> savings towards retirement each year and enter those into this calculator on the left.  
                    We will assume you'll continue saving the same amount going forward each year.
                  </p>
                  <a class="btn btn-success nextbtn" href="#inContributions" data-tab="#tab_savings" data-toggle="tab" role="button">Next: Other Retirement Contributions</a>
                </div>
