                    The chart below shows how your retirement income changes based on when you start your social security benefits.
                  </p>
                  <a class="btn btn-success nextbtn" href="#inRetirementAge" data-tab="#tab_retirement" data-toggle="tab" role="button">Next: Retirement Age</a>
                </div>
                <div class="tab-pane" id="inRetirementAge">
                  <h2>Retirement Age </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>Happiness: a good bank account, a good cook and a good digestion. -<a href="https://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Talk:Jean-Jacques_Rousseau">Rousseau</a></small></p>
                  <p>
                    When you stop working has a huge affect on your retirement income.  An early retirement means less time for your retirement savings to grow, and your savings will need to last longer.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    This calculator assumes you withdraw roughly the same amount each year for retirement, 
                    <a href="https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Models_of_spending_as_retirement_progresses#Stages_of_retirement_models" target="_blank">adjusting for expenses over time based on your age</a>.  
                    In general, retirees spend more during their early retirement as they travel, pay off mortgages, and children become less dependant on assistance from parents.  
                    By around 75 or 80 years of age, retirees spend significantly less money during retirement.  After that, retirement spending grows with increasing medical expenses.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Basically, the earlier you retire, the less money you will have to spend. 
                    If you retire before you start collecting social security, you may need to withdraw more from your savings which could increase your chances of running out of money.
                  </p>
                  <a class="btn btn-success nextbtn" href="#inLifeExpectancy" data-tab="#tab_retirement" data-toggle="tab" role="button">Next: Life Expectancy</a>
                </div>
                <div class="tab-pane" id="inLifeExpectancy">
                  <h2>Life Expectancy </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>There's never enough time to do all the nothing you want. -<i>Calvin and Hobbes</i></small></p>
                  <p>
                    While we have some control over when we decide to retire, we have much less control over how long we will live.
                    The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_the_verified_oldest_people" target="_blank">oldest verified living person</a> lived for over <strong>122 years</strong>.  
                    According to a <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nvsr/nvsr54/nvsr54_14.pdf" target="_blank">2006 Center for Disease Control (CDC) report</a>, 
                    over 2% of people live to 100.  That means 1 out of every 50 people will live to 100.  And, those who live to 100 can expect to live another 2.5 years.  
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Planning to live to 103 years of age and having your savings last until then is a good start.  You do not want to run out of money and die in poverty.
                  </p>
                  <a class="btn btn-success nextbtn" href="#inWithdrawalRate" data-tab="#tab_retirement" data-toggle="tab" role="button">Next: Withdrawal Rate</a>
                </div>
                <div class="tab-pane" id="inWithdrawalRate">
                  <h2>Withdrawal Rate </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>Money is better than poverty, if only for financial reasons. -Woody Allen</small></p>
                  <p>
                    The <a href="https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Safe_withdrawal_rates">"safe withdrawal rate"</a> is considered to be <a href="https://www.google.com/?hl=en#hl=en&q=safe+withdrawal+rate">4%</a>.
                    However, a 4% withdrawal rate may not be safe for everyone now.
                    The safe withdrawal rate was calculated as the amount of money someone can withdraw each year (4%) from their savings so that it is unlikely to run out of money over 30 years.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    The 4% value was a great rule of thumb when most people retired at 60, with 30 years of savings, and lived to 80 or 85.  
                    Basically, retirees were more likely to die before they ran out of money. 
                    Today, people tend to live longer now with <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nvsr/nvsr54/nvsr54_14.pdf" target="_blank">more than 1 out of every 50 people</a> living over 100 years.  
                    If you retire at 65 and run out of money 30 years later at 95 years of age, you could be living very miserably in poverty for the final years of your life.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    A safer withdrawal rate is now as low as 3% for most people.  For example, if you retire at 65 with a 3% withdrawal rate, your retirement savings will last until you are 100 years old.  
                    By comparison, if you retire at 65 with a 4% withdrawal rate, your retirement savings will only last until you are 91 years old.  
                    You'll avoid dying in poverty by living more frugally in retirement.
                  </p>
                  <a class="btn btn-success nextbtn" href="#inOwn" data-tab="#tab_retirement" data-toggle="tab" role="button">Next: Housing Payments</a>
                </div>
                <div class="tab-pane" id="inOwn">
                  <h2>Housing </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>Owning a home is a keystone of wealth... -Suze Orman</small></p>
                  <div id="fieldHousingMortgagePayOff" class="well pull-right">
                    <div class="showHousingToggle housingRent text-center">
                      <i class="fa fa-home fa-5x"></i>
                      <p class="h4"><small>The home should be the treasure chest of living. <br>-Le Corbusier</small></p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="showHousingToggle housingMortgage">
                      Assuming you pay off your house in <span class="badgeData">30</span> years...
                      <br>
                      <input id="fieldHousingPaidOff" type="text" class="form-control slider" value="30" data-slider-min="0" data-slider-max="60" data-slider-step="1" data-slider-value="30" 
                             data-slider-orientation="horizontal" data-slider-selection="after" data-slider-tooltip="hide">
                      <br>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <p>
                    Housing is one of the single largest expenses for any person whether working or retired.  If you rent your home forever, you must budget for paying rent every year.  
                    That includes budgeting for rent in retirement.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    A better approach for retirement is to put your housing payment towards a home so that your house is paid off in 15 to 30 years.  
                    Once your house is paid off, you won't have a housing payment to budget for.
                    Without a housing payment, your retirement savings will go much further <em>and</em>, if you need to, you can use your house for income in retirement.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    If you do have a mortgage, a <strong><span style='color: purple'>purple line</span></strong> on chart below shows your living expenses excluding your mortgage.  
                  </p>
