                      <label> Stock Market - 7% </label>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <p class="small">
                    <sup>1</sup> The cited article actually quotes Warren Buffet who estimates a 7% return including inflation.  This calculator defaults to 7% <i>before</i> inflation to be more conservative.
                    You can read more about <a href="https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Historical_and_expected_returns" target=_blank>historical returns</a>, 
                    but keep in mind that "past performance is not an indicator of future results".  Feel free to adjust the estimated return slider in accordance with your expected returns.
                  </p>
                  <p class="small">
                  <sup>2</sup> See also, this <a href="http://pages.stern.nyu.edu/~adamodar/New_Home_Page/datafile/histretSP.html" target="_blank">analysis</a> showing worst case scenarios of approximately: 
                    7% return for S&P 500, 1% for Short Term Government Bonds, and 4.7% for Long Term Government Bonds.  This calculator rounds down to be more conservative.
                    Feel free to adjust the estimated return slider in accordance with your expected returns.
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div class="tab-pane" id="inRetirementROI">
                  <h2>Safer Investments During Retirement </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>An investment in knowledge pays the best interest. -Benjamin Franklin</small></p>
                  <p>
                    Risk is dangerous in retirement.  A poorly timed market crash or recession can severely impact your retirement savings.
                    To avoid these risks, many retirees switch their retirement savings over to much safer investments like inflation protected treasury bonds that pay a much lower interest rate.
                    Less risk, less return.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    To err on the side of caution, this calculator defaults to assuming your retirement savings will keep pace with inflation with little or no real return after inflation.
                  </p>
                  <p class="small">
                    By default, this calculator uses a more conservative number but, technically, safe investments like US Treasury Bills return a little more, about 0.5% higher, than the inflation rate.
                    You can read more about <a href="https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Historical_and_expected_returns" target=_blank>historical returns</a>, 
                    but keep in mind that "past performance is not an indicator of future results".  Feel free to adjust the estimated return slider in accordance with your expected returns.
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div class="tab-pane" id="inInflation">
                  <h2>Inflation </h2>
                  <p class="h3"><small>A nickel ain’t worth a dime anymore. –Yogi Berra</small></p>
                  <p>
                    Unfortunately, the same compounding that grew your nest egg savings quickly also works against you in retirement as 
                    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation" target="_blank">inflation</a>.  Over time, the value of each dollar you haved saved up diminishes by a small amount.  Historically,
                    the average inflation rate in the US is <a href="http://inflationdata.com/Inflation/Inflation_Rate/Long_Term_Inflation.asp" target="_blank">3.22%</a> which means prices double every 
                    20 years or so.  Since inflation works against you, this calculator defaults to a slightly more cautious inflation rate of 4%.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    A 4% annual inflation rate means that if you spend $10,000 this year on living expenses, in 18 years you will need $20,000 for the exact same living expenses!  As a result, you will
                    withdraw more money from savings each year just to maintain your lifestyle.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    In order to make things easier, this calculator accounts for inflation so you can compare <i>in today's dollars</i> your current budget to your retirement budget.
                  </p>
